{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d56ee895-06e2-4935-a0c9-c1479c1a7384","content":"This is a TUnit project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). To run only `SmsNotificationTests`, use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nSince TUnit is MTP-native (note the `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`), you pass filters after `--`. The `--treenode-filter` uses a path-like syntax where `**` matches any segments, so this selects all tests under the `SmsNotificationTests` class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7a6212ab-a82b-4034-ab46-76dbd67eb8c3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (not MSTest/xUnit/NUnit). TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. To filter by class, the command would use the MTP filter syntax.\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, to filter by class name:\n\n```\ndotnet run --filter-class *SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nOr using `dotnet test` with VSTest filter syntax... but TUnit uses MTP natively since it's an `Exe` OutputType. Let me check — TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP by default.\n\nWith MTP, the filter syntax is:\n\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --filter-class *SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nOr alternatively with `dotnet test`:\n```\ndotnet test -- --filter-class *SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nThe `--filter-class` flag is the MTP-specific way to filter tests by class name.\n\nFor TUnit specifically, which uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform, I should verify the exact syntax. The treenode filter approach would be `--treenode-filter` with a pattern like `\"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"`, but the simpler `--filter-class` option is likely more straightforward for filtering by class name.","outputTokens":679},"id":"9d83092c-e185-485d-8a7e-9faa189e1621","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:23:02.301Z","parentId":"2f118fbc-ad14-4252-a0f0-2ed2d0de1ee9"}
